-> Adapter Pattern
Intent:
Convert the interface of a class into another interface clients expect.
👉 Used when you want to reuse existing code but interfaces don’t match.

// Target
interface Charger {
    void charge();
}

// Adaptee (existing class)
class OldCharger {
    void plugIn() {
        System.out.println("Charging using old charger");
    }
}

// Adapter
class ChargerAdapter implements Charger {
    private OldCharger oldCharger;

    ChargerAdapter(OldCharger oldCharger) {
        this.oldCharger = oldCharger;
    }

    public void charge() {
        oldCharger.plugIn();
    }
}

// Client
public class AdapterDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Charger charger = new ChargerAdapter(new OldCharger());
        charger.charge();
    }
}


-> Composite Pattern
Treat individual objects and compositions of objects uniformly.
👉 Common in tree structures (files, menus, UI components).

interface FileComponent {
    void show();
}

// Leaf
class File implements FileComponent {
    private String name;

    File(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("File: " + name);
    }
}

// Composite
class Directory implements FileComponent {
    private String name;
    private List<FileComponent> children = new ArrayList<>();

    Directory(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void add(FileComponent component) {
        children.add(component);
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Directory: " + name);
        for (FileComponent c : children) {
            c.show();
        }
    }
}


-> Facade Pattern
Provide a simple interface to a complex subsystem.
👉 Very common in service layers, APIs, libraries.

class DVDPlayer {
    void on() { System.out.println("DVD ON"); }
}

class SoundSystem {
    void setVolume() { System.out.println("Sound set"); }
}

class Projector {
    void on() { System.out.println("Projector ON"); }
}

// Facade
class HomeTheaterFacade {
    private DVDPlayer dvd = new DVDPlayer();
    private SoundSystem sound = new SoundSystem();
    private Projector projector = new Projector();

    void watchMovie() {
        dvd.on();
        sound.setVolume();
        projector.on();
        System.out.println("Movie started");
    }
}


-> Decorator Pattern
Add behavior to an object dynamically without modifying its class.
👉 Alternative to subclass explosion.

interface Coffee {
    int cost();
}

// Base object
class SimpleCoffee implements Coffee {
    public int cost() {
        return 100;
    }
}

// Decorator
abstract class CoffeeDecorator implements Coffee {
    protected Coffee coffee;

    CoffeeDecorator(Coffee coffee) {
        this.coffee = coffee;
    }
}

// Concrete decorator
class MilkDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    MilkDecorator(Coffee coffee) {
        super(coffee);
    }

    public int cost() {
        return coffee.cost() + 20;
    }
}


-> Bridge Pattern
Decouple abstraction from implementation so both can vary independently.
👉 Prevents class explosion.

// Implementor
interface Device {
    void turnOn();
}

class TV implements Device {
    public void turnOn() {
        System.out.println("TV ON");
    }
}

// Abstraction
abstract class Remote {
    protected Device device;

    Remote(Device device) {
        this.device = device;
    }

    abstract void power();
}

// Refined abstraction
class BasicRemote extends Remote {
    BasicRemote(Device device) {
        super(device);
    }

    void power() {
        device.turnOn();
    }
}


-> Proxy Pattern

Provide a placeholder or wrapper to control access to another object.
👉 Used for security, lazy loading, logging.

interface Image {
    void display();
}

class RealImage implements Image {
    private String file;

    RealImage(String file) {
        this.file = file;
        load();
    }

    private void load() {
        System.out.println("Loading " + file);
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Displaying " + file);
    }
}

// Proxy
class ImageProxy implements Image {
    private RealImage realImage;
    private String file;

    ImageProxy(String file) {
        this.file = file;
    }

    public void display() {
        if (realImage == null) {
            realImage = new RealImage(file);
        }
        realImage.display();
    }
}

-> Flyweight Pattern

Reduce memory by sharing common immutable state.
👉 Useful when you have lots of similar objects.

class CharacterFlyweight {
    private final char symbol;

    CharacterFlyweight(char symbol) {
        this.symbol = symbol;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.print(symbol);
    }
}

// Factory
class CharacterFactory {
    private static final Map<Character, CharacterFlyweight> cache = new HashMap<>();

    static CharacterFlyweight get(char c) {
        return cache.computeIfAbsent(c, CharacterFlyweight::new);
    }
}
